searchData={"items":[{"type":"task","title":"mix spex","doc":"Mix task that checks saved implementation models for behavioural equivalence.\n\nThis is the offline verification entry point for `.spex` model files.","ref":"Mix.Tasks.Spex.html"},{"type":"function","title":"Mix.Tasks.Spex.run/1","doc":"Runs Spex behavioural equivalence checks for all loaded implementation models.\n\nAccepts either no arguments (uses configured `:impl_models_dir`) or one path argument to a\ndirectory or file containing `.spex` models.\n\nIf an implementation model is found to be not behaviourally equivalent to its specification, a\nwarning is logged and the task exits with status code 1. Currently, it is not possible to give\ninformation about _why_ they are not equivalent. It is up to the developer to analyse the\nimplementation model and compare it to its specification.","ref":"Mix.Tasks.Spex.html#run/1"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex","doc":"Entry point for Spex runtime APIs and high-level integration.","ref":"Spex.html"},{"type":"module","title":"Install, configure, and start Spex - Spex","doc":"Add Spex to your dependencies:\n\n    def deps do\n    [\n      {:spex, \"~> 0.1.1\", hex: :lts_spex}\n    ]\n    end\n\nPlease note the `hex: :lts_spex`.\nThe package name `:spex` itself was [already taken](https://hex.pm/packages/spex) (which I\nrealised only after becoming attached to the name). However, since that package is unmaintained\nand not widely used, I decided to keep the namespace simply as `Spex`. The _lts_ prefix stands for\n_labelled transition system_ (see the [Theoretical background section of the readme](README.md#theoretical-background)).\n\nOptionally, add `:spex` to your [`.formatter.exs` file under `:import_deps`](https://hexdocs.pm/mix/main/Mix.Tasks.Format.html#module-importing-dependencies-configuration).","ref":"Spex.html#module-install-configure-and-start-spex"},{"type":"module","title":"Configuration - Spex","doc":"The derived implementation models are stored in a custom format in a given folder. Ideally, this\nshould be within the priv directory of your application (`:code.priv_dir(:your_app)`).\n\n[`:dets`](https://www.erlang.org/doc/apps/stdlib/dets.html) is used to persist information about\ninstances (like previous transitions). You can configure the directory in which these dets files\nare stored.\n\nWhen you specify a transition timeout in your specification (see `Spex.Specification`), timeouts\nare detected and reported. You might or might not want to have these timeouts checked at\napplication startup for persisted instances. Enabling it might lead to many timeout reports at\nstartup, disabling it might lead to missed timeouts.\n\nSimilarly, you can specify prunable states and prune timeouts to avoid storing instances\nindefinitely. You can configure how often this pruning should happen.\n\nHere is a sample configuration with the default values:\n\n    config :spex,\n      impl_models_dir: \"./spex_impl_models\",\n      dets_dir: \"./spex_dets\",\n      check_transition_timeouts_on_start?: true,\n      prune_interval: %Duration{hour: 6} |> to_timeout()","ref":"Spex.html#module-configuration"},{"type":"module","title":"Manual Supervision - Spex","doc":"By default, Spex starts its own application incl. supervision tree and is usable right away. If\nyou'd rather supervise it yourself, you can also disable the Spex application and add it to your\nsupervision tree manually:\n\n    def deps do\n    [\n      {:spex, \"~> 0.1.1\", hex: :lts_spex, runtime: false}\n    ]\n    end\n\n\n    children = [\n      ...,\n      {Spex, spex_config_opts}\n    ]\n\n    Supervisor.start(children, supervisor_opts)\n\nNote that you can pass spex_config_opts to Spex here. These options are the same as the ones\ndescribed in the configuration section above.","ref":"Spex.html#module-manual-supervision"},{"type":"module","title":"Using other instance managers - Spex","doc":"By default, `Spex` is a convenience front for the `Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager`,\nwhich starts a single GenServer that handles all instances. Should this become a bottleneck, there\nis also the `Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager`. To use it, you can configure it as\nfollows (note that this a compile time config):\n\n    config :spex,\n      instance_manager: Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager,\n      instance_manager_opts: [distribution_factor: 4] # 4 is the default\n\nAlternatively, you can also add either instance manager to your supervision tree directly, e.g.:\n\n    children = [\n      ...,\n      # spex_config_opts are the same as the ones described in the configuration section above\n      {Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager, [distribution_factor: 4] ++ spex_config_opts}\n    ]\n\n    Supervisor.start(children, supervisor_opts)\n\nIf you choose to do this, however, do note that `Spex` does no longer work as a convenience front\nand you need to make all calls to your chosen instance manager directly (e.g.\n`Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.transition(...)` rather than\n`Spex.transition(...)`).","ref":"Spex.html#module-using-other-instance-managers"},{"type":"module","title":"Define specifications - Spex","doc":"Specifications represent protocols or workflows and are modelled as graphs / state machines. The\nfocus lies on the transitions (edges) rather than the states (nodes): when we compare an\nimplementation model against its specification, their states can be entirely distinct, since\nbehavioural equivalence is judged entirely based on their transition behaviours (basically: action\nsequences).\n\nIn the simplest case, you can create a specification as follows:\n\n    defmodule YourApp.Specifications.Tree do\n      @moduledoc \"\"\"\n      A specification that forms a small, simple tree structure:\n\n                   s0\n                  /  |\n                a/    |a\n                /      |\n              s1       s2\n              / |\n            b/   |c\n            /     |\n          s3      s4\n\n      \"\"\"\n      use Spex.Specification\n\n      def_transition :s0, :a, :s1\n      def_transition :s0, :a, :s2\n\n      def_transition :s1, :b, :s3\n      def_transition :s1, :c, :s4\n    end\n\nEach _transition_ consists of a _from_state_, an _action_, and a _to_state_.\n\nSpecifications can have custom error handlers, to which any reported errors are passed for\nprocessing, e.g. logging and deciding which errors are okay.\n\nFor details on configuring and customising specifications, see `Spex.Specification`.","ref":"Spex.html#module-define-specifications"},{"type":"module","title":"Observe transitions in your implementation - Spex","doc":"In your actual implementation code, you need to initialise instances of your specification and\nrecord transitions.\n\nAs a useless toy example, say we manage a pine forest where each pine has a number. We offer a\nfunction for planting a seedling:\n\n    alias YourApp.Specifications.Tree\n\n    def plant_seedling(pine_id) do\n      specification = Tree\n      instance_identifier = {Tree, pine_id}\n      meta = %{planting_datetime: DateTime.utc_now()}\n      initial_state = :seedling\n\n      Spex.init_instance(specification, instance_identifier, meta, initial_state)\n    end\n\nNote that the instance identifier is an arbitrary term that uniquely identifies the instance\nacross all specifications (hence it can make sense to include the specification module). The meta\ncan optionally be added to make possible error reports regarding the instance more useful. The\ninitial state is also optional and defaults to the specification's initial state.\n\nAfter an instance is initialised, we can record its transitions with\n`Spex.transition(instance_identifier, action, new_state)`:\n\n    def pour_onto(pine_id, :water), do: Spex.transition({Tree, pine_id}, :a, :sapling)\n    def pour_onto(pine_id, :oil), do: Spex.transition({Tree, pine_id}, :a, :withered)\n    def observe_growth(pine_id), do: Spex.transition({Tree, pine_id}, :__internal__, :mature_tree)\n    def cut_down(pine_id), do: Spex.transition({Tree, pine_id}, :b, :lumber)\n    def burn(pine_id), do: Spex.transition({Tree, pine_id}, :c, :ash)\n\nAs mentioned above, the states do not have to match the specification states. The actions,\nhowever, do need to match, as these are what the behavioural equivalence is judged on.\n\nAn exception to this and a useful addition is the `__internal__` action, which can be used to\nrecord internal state transitions that are not part of the specification but that you still want\nto be recorded in the implementation model. These are ignored (or rather: treated specially) for\nthe behavioural equivalence checks.\n\nBoth `Spex.init_instance/4` and `Spex.transition/3` will return `:ok` on success or\n`{:error, error}` on failure; this error will be one of the errors from `Spex.Errors` by default.\nIf you configured a custom error handler in your specifications (see `Spex.Specification`), the\nfunctions will return whatever your error handler returned for the given error.\n\nThere are also, `Spex.init_instance!/4` and `Spex.transition!/3`, which raise when their non-bang\ncounterparts would return an error. Since these errors point to bugs in your implementation, using\nthese bang variants might be reasonable.\n\nOn the other end, there are `Spex.init_instance_async/4` and `Spex.transition_async/3`, which\nasynchronously cast to the underlying GenServer and always return `:ok`. Error handling is then\nentirely up to your specifications' error handlers and impact on the running system is minimised.","ref":"Spex.html#module-observe-transitions-in-your-implementation"},{"type":"module","title":"Derive implementation models: in tests - Spex","doc":"Your tests should cover all possible transitions of your implementation, so we can use them to\nderive an implementation model. To do this, add the following to your `test_helper.exs`:\n\n    Spex.Testing.prepare_for_test_suite()\n\nThis prepares the Spex engine to record all transitions from tests and write derived\nimplementation models in the directory configured above.\n\nIn unit tests, we often construct our parameters to be in a certain state. When using\n`Spex.init_instance/4`, though, the given initial state is added as an initial state of the\nimplementation model, which we don't want in these cases. To construct an instance in a certain\nstate without affecting the implementation model, there is `Spex.Testing.mock_instance!/4`. In a\ntest for our pine forest above, you might do something like this:\n\n    alias YourApp.Specifications.Tree\n\n    Spex.Testing.mock_instance!(Tree, {Tree, 1}, :mature_tree)\n\n    assert YourApp.Pine.cut_down(1) == :ok\n\nSince `cut_down/1` calls `Spex.transition({Tree, pine_id}, :b, :lumber)`, this test would add a\ntransition from state `:mature_tree` with action `:b` to state `:lumber` to the implementation\nmodel.","ref":"Spex.html#module-derive-implementation-models-in-tests"},{"type":"module","title":"Derive implementation models: live - Spex","doc":"When running in non-test environments, Spex expects all implementation models to exist already. If\nyou'd rather derive your implementation models live, you can either (1) ignore\nimplementation-model-not-found errors or (2) create empty implementation models in learning mode.\n\nFor (1), adjust/add an error handler in your specifications, e.g. as so:\n\n    defmodule YourApp.Specifications.Tree do\n      use Spex.Specification\n\n      #...\n\n      @impl Spex.Specification\n      def error_handler(%Spex.Errors.ImplModelError{reason: :impl_model_not_found}, _caller), do: :ok\n      def error_handler(error, caller), do: super(error, caller)\n    end\n\nFor (2), for each specification, create a file\n`\"Elixir.YourApp.Specifications.[YOUR_SPECIFICATION].spex` in your configured implementation model\ndirectory (`:impl_models_dir`) with this content:\n\n```text\nSpecification: Elixir.YourApp.Specifications.[YOUR_SPECIFICATION]\nLearning mode: true\nTransitions:\n```\n\nFor both options, when you think that all transitions have been recorded, via a remote shell, call\n`Spex.export_impl_models()`. This will return a list of tuples `{filename, serialisation}`, which\nyou can then store in your implementation model directory (with the given filename and the\nserialisation as content).","ref":"Spex.html#module-derive-implementation-models-live"},{"type":"module","title":"Check behavioural equivalence: offline - Spex","doc":"After implementation models have been derived and stored, you can run `mix spex` (see\n`Mix.Tasks.Spex`) to check whether they are behaviourally equivalent. Currently, the output only\ntells you _if_ an implementation model is not behaviourally equivalent to its specification and\nyou are required to analyse the model to understand why.","ref":"Spex.html#module-check-behavioural-equivalence-offline"},{"type":"module","title":"Check behavioural equivalence: online - Spex","doc":"Once you have derived implementation models that were deemed behaviourally equivalent to their\nspecification, you are ready to use Spex in production. Every time you initialise and instance or\nrecord a transition, it is checked whether the initialisation or transition is part of the\nimplementation model. If it is, all is well. If it isn't, a behavioural equivalence check on the\nresultant model against the specification is run. In any case, an `%Spex.Errors.InstanceError{}`\nis reported, either with `:reason` being `:deviation_still_equivalent` or\n`:deviation_not_equivalent`. It is up to your specification's error handler to handle these cases\naccordingly (e.g. log the occurrence but still return `:ok` in the former case). The reason is\nthat even deviations that don't break the equivalence hint at scenarios your tests don't cover.\nYou can then fix these reports in the future by adding a test that covers the transition or by\nadding the transition manually to your implementation model.","ref":"Spex.html#module-check-behavioural-equivalence-online"},{"type":"module","title":"Manual instance management - Spex","doc":"To inspect or delete the instances managed by an instance manager, each instance manager offers\nmore functionality than that exposed through `Spex`. See\n`Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager` and `Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager`\nfor details.","ref":"Spex.html#module-manual-instance-management"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.action/0","doc":"Action label on transitions.\n\nConventional reserved actions used internally by Spex are:\n\n- `:__internal__` for unobservable/internal steps,\n- `:__initialisation__` for synthetic instance initialization transitions.","ref":"Spex.html#t:action/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.state/0","doc":"State label used in specifications and runtime observations.","ref":"Spex.html#t:state/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.transition/0","doc":"A labelled transition tuple `{from_state, action, to_state}`.","ref":"Spex.html#t:transition/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.child_spec/1","doc":"","ref":"Spex.html#child_spec/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.export_impl_models/0","doc":"See  Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.export_impl_models/0 .","ref":"Spex.html#export_impl_models/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.init_instance/4","doc":"See  Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.init_instance/4 .","ref":"Spex.html#init_instance/4"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.init_instance!/4","doc":"See  Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.init_instance!/4 .","ref":"Spex.html#init_instance!/4"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.init_instance_async/4","doc":"See  Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.init_instance_async/4 .","ref":"Spex.html#init_instance_async/4"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.transition/3","doc":"See  Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.transition/3 .","ref":"Spex.html#transition/3"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.transition!/3","doc":"See  Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.transition!/3 .","ref":"Spex.html#transition!/3"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.transition_async/3","doc":"See  Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.transition_async/3 .","ref":"Spex.html#transition_async/3"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.Application","doc":"Application entrypoint for starting the Spex supervision tree.","ref":"Spex.Application.html"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.BisimilarityChecker","doc":"Compares implementation models against specifications via branching bisimilarity.","ref":"Spex.BisimilarityChecker.html"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.BisimilarityChecker.bisimilar_to_specification?/1","doc":"Compares an ImplModel against its Specification using bisimilarity checking.\n\nReturns `true` if the implementation model is bisimilar to the specification, `false` otherwise.","ref":"Spex.BisimilarityChecker.html#bisimilar_to_specification?/1"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.BisimilarityChecker.MercWrapper","doc":"Rust NIF wrapper used to execute bisimilarity checks.","ref":"Spex.BisimilarityChecker.MercWrapper.html"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.BisimilarityChecker.MercWrapper.compare_bisimilarity/2","doc":"Compares implementation and specification LTS data for branching bisimilarity.","ref":"Spex.BisimilarityChecker.MercWrapper.html#compare_bisimilarity/2"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.Errors","doc":"Error types used across Spex runtime and persistence boundaries.","ref":"Spex.Errors.html"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.Errors.FileError","doc":"Alias type wrapper for file-system errors represented by `File.Error`.","ref":"Spex.Errors.FileError.html"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.Errors.FileError.t/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.Errors.FileError.html#t:t/0"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.Errors.Template","doc":"Macro for defining Spex exception modules with typed reasons and context.","ref":"Spex.Errors.Template.html"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.ImplModel","doc":"Represents the observed implementation model built from runtime transitions.","ref":"Spex.ImplModel.html"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.ImplModel.observation_status/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.ImplModel.html#t:observation_status/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.ImplModel.serialisation/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.ImplModel.html#t:serialisation/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.ImplModel.t/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.ImplModel.html#t:t/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.ImplModel.deserialise/1","doc":"Deserialises `.spex` content into an implementation model.","ref":"Spex.ImplModel.html#deserialise/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.ImplModel.initialise/1","doc":"Creates an empty implementation model for a specification in learning mode.","ref":"Spex.ImplModel.html#initialise/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.ImplModel.observe_transition/2","doc":"Observes a transition and returns its status and resulting model.\n\nIn learning mode, the transition is added. Outside learning mode, the model\nis checked for bisimilarity impact without mutating stored transitions.","ref":"Spex.ImplModel.html#observe_transition/2"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.ImplModel.serialise/1","doc":"Serialises an implementation model into `.spex` text format. For info on the format, just see the\nimplementation of this function.","ref":"Spex.ImplModel.html#serialise/1"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.ImplModelStore","doc":"Loads and persists implementation models in `.spex` file format.","ref":"Spex.ImplModelStore.html"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.ImplModelStore.load/1","doc":"Loads all `.spex` models from a directory or a single file path.","ref":"Spex.ImplModelStore.html#load/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.ImplModelStore.save/2","doc":"Saves implementation models to the target directory.\n\nReturns all write errors if one or more files fail to persist.","ref":"Spex.ImplModelStore.html#save/2"},{"type":"behaviour","title":"Spex.InstanceManager","doc":"Behaviour contract plus shared helpers for Spex instance managers.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.instance_manager_opt/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#t:instance_manager_opt/0"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.all_impl_models/0","doc":"Returns all currently known implementation models.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:all_impl_models/0"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.all_instances/0","doc":"Returns all instances managed by this instance manager.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:all_instances/0"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.all_instances/1","doc":"Returns all instances for a given specification module.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:all_instances/1"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.child_spec/1","doc":"Returns a child spec for supervising the instance manager.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:child_spec/1"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.delete_instance/1","doc":"Deletes one instance by identifier.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:delete_instance/1"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.delete_instances/1","doc":"Deletes all instances matching the provided filter function.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:delete_instances/1"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.export_impl_models/0","doc":"Serialises and exports implementation models as `{filename, content}` tuples.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:export_impl_models/0"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.get_instance/1","doc":"Fetches one instance by identifier.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:get_instance/1"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.init_instance/4","doc":"Initializes a new instance and records initialisation as the first transition.\n\nReturns `:ok` on success or an error-handler return when initialization fails.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:init_instance/4"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.init_instance!/4","doc":"Same as `init_instance/4`, but raises on errors.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:init_instance!/4"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.init_instance_async/4","doc":"Asynchronously initializes a new instance.\n\nErrors are reported via specification error handling instead of direct return.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:init_instance_async/4"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.mock_instance!/4","doc":"Inserts or updates a mock instance at a given state for testing purposes.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:mock_instance!/4"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.start_link/1","doc":"Starts the instance manager process tree.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:start_link/1"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.transition/3","doc":"Records an observed transition for an existing instance.\n\nReturns `:ok` on success or an error-handler return when validation/storage fails.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:transition/3"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.transition!/3","doc":"Same as `transition/3`, but raises on errors.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:transition!/3"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.transition_async/3","doc":"Asynchronously records a transition for an existing instance.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#c:transition_async/3"},{"type":"macro","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.__using__/1","doc":"Injects the `Spex.InstanceManager` behaviour and shared convenience functions.\n\nGenerated convenience functions:\n\n- `child_spec/1`\n- `init_instance!/4`\n- `transition!/3`","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#__using__/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.default_instance_manager/0","doc":"Returns the compile-time configured default instance manager module.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#default_instance_manager/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.default_instance_manager_opts/0","doc":"Returns compile-time options for the default instance manager.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.html#default_instance_manager_opts/0"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager","doc":"Instance manager that shards instances across multiple `Spex.InstanceManager.Server` processes.\n\nThis manager hashes each instance identifier and routes operations to one of\nseveral server shards. It is useful when you want to reduce contention versus\na single-manager setup while preserving the same high-level API.\n\nSee `m:Spex#module-using-other-instance-managers` for info on using this instance manager.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html"},{"type":"module","title":"Configuration - Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager","doc":"This manager accepts one distribution-specific option (`:distribution_factor`) plus server options\nforwarded to each shard (`Spex.InstanceManager.Server.server_opt()`).\n\n- `:distribution_factor` (`pos_integer()`)\n  Number of server shards.\n  Default: `4`.\n  Must be a positive integer; otherwise `start_link/1` raises `ArgumentError`.\n\n- `:dets_table` is set per shard by this module\n  (`Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.Server_ `), so callers should not provide\n  it.\n\n- For the other opts, see `Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager`","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#module-configuration"},{"type":"module","title":"Routing semantics - Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager","doc":"Instance routing is deterministic:\n\n- hash = `:erlang.phash2(instance_identifier)`\n- shard index = `rem(hash, distribution_factor) + 1`\n\nAll operations for a given instance identifier are routed to the same shard.\n\nMethods that aggregate globally (`all_instances/0`, `all_instances/1`, `delete_instances/1`,\n`all_impl_models/0`) query all shards and combine the results.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#module-routing-semantics"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.all_impl_models/0","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.all_impl_models/0`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#all_impl_models/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.all_instances/0","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.all_instances/0`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#all_instances/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.all_instances/1","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.all_instances/1`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#all_instances/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.child_spec/1","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.child_spec/1`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#child_spec/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.delete_instance/1","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.delete_instance/1`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#delete_instance/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.delete_instances/1","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.delete_instances/1`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#delete_instances/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.export_impl_models/0","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.export_impl_models/0`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#export_impl_models/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.get_instance/1","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.get_instance/1`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#get_instance/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.init_instance/4","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.init_instance/4`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#init_instance/4"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.init_instance!/4","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.init_instance!/4`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#init_instance!/4"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.init_instance_async/4","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.init_instance_async/4`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#init_instance_async/4"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.mock_instance!/4","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.mock_instance!/4`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#mock_instance!/4"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.start_link/1","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.start_link/1`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#start_link/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.transition/3","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.transition/3`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#transition/3"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.transition!/3","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.transition!/3`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#transition!/3"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.transition_async/3","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.transition_async/3`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.html#transition_async/3"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.DistributionFactorState","doc":"Agent storing the configured distribution factor.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.DistributionFactorState.html"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.DistributionFactorState.distribution_factor/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.DistributionFactorState.html#t:distribution_factor/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.DistributionFactorState.child_spec/1","doc":"Returns a specification to start this module under a supervisor.\n\nSee `Supervisor`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.DistributionFactorState.html#child_spec/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.DistributionFactorState.get/0","doc":"Returns the currently configured distribution factor.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.DistributionFactorState.html#get/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.DistributionFactorState.start_link/1","doc":"Starts the distribution-factor agent.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.DistributedInstanceManager.DistributionFactorState.html#start_link/1"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance","doc":"Runtime representation of a specification instance and its observed history.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.html"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.instance_identifier/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.html#t:instance_identifier/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.meta/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.html#t:meta/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.t/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.html#t:t/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.transition_record/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.html#t:transition_record/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.beyond_transition_timeout?/2","doc":"Returns whether the instance exceeded its specification transition timeout.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.html#beyond_transition_timeout?/2"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.initialise/3","doc":"Initialises a new instance with an empty transition history.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.html#initialise/3"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.observe_transition/3","doc":"Records an observed transition and updates the current state.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.html#observe_transition/3"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.prunable?/1","doc":"Returns whether the instance is currently eligible for pruning.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Instance.html#prunable?/1"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore","doc":"Abstraction layer for instance storage using DETS.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.html"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.instance_hash/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.html#t:instance_hash/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.all/1","doc":"Gets all instances.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.html#all/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.all/2","doc":"Gets all instances for a specific specification.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.html#all/2"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.close/1","doc":"Closes the DETS table.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.html#close/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.delete/2","doc":"Deletes an instance by hash.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.html#delete/2"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.delete_matching/2","doc":"Deletes instances matching the given filter function.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.html#delete_matching/2"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.exists?/2","doc":"Checks if an instance exists for the given hash.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.html#exists?/2"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.get/2","doc":"Gets an instance by hash.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.html#get/2"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.init/2","doc":"Initializes the DETS table for storing instances.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.html#init/2"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.put/2","doc":"Stores an instance with the given hash.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.html#put/2"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.traverse/2","doc":"Traverses all instances with the given function.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.html#traverse/2"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.truncate/1","doc":"Deletes all instances from the DETS table.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.InstanceStore.html#truncate/1"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Server","doc":"Core GenServer that manages instances and implementation-model observation.\n\nThis process is the stateful runtime engine behind instance managers.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Server.html"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Server.impl_models_map/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Server.html#t:impl_models_map/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Server.server_opt/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Server.html#t:server_opt/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Server.server_state/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Server.html#t:server_state/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.Server.child_spec/1","doc":"Returns a specification to start this module under a supervisor.\n\nSee `Supervisor`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.Server.html#child_spec/1"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager","doc":"Single-node instance manager backed by one `Spex.InstanceManager.Server` process.\n\nUse this manager when you want all instance operations handled by a single\nGenServer and a single DETS table.\n\nSee `m:Spex#module-using-other-instance-managers` for info on using this instance manager.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html"},{"type":"module","title":"Configuration - Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager","doc":"`SimpleInstanceManager` forwards server options to `Spex.InstanceManager.Server` (see\n`Spex.InstanceManager.Server.server_opt()`), with one internal detail:\n\n- `:dets_table` is always set to `Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager` by this module and\n  should not be provided by callers.\n\nSupported options (see `m:Spex#module-configuration`):\n\n- `:impl_models_dir` (`String.t()`)\n  Path to `.spex` implementation model files loaded on startup.\n  Default: value from config or else `\"./spex_impl_models\"`.\n\n- `:dets_dir` (`String.t()`)\n  Directory where the DETS file for this manager is stored.\n  Default: value from config or else `\"./spex_dets\"`.\n\n- `:check_transition_timeouts_on_start?` (`boolean()`)\n  When `true`, existing instances in DETS are checked during startup and transition timeout errors\n  are emitted if needed.\n  Default: `true`.\n\n- `:prune_interval` (`timeout()`)\n  Interval for periodic pruning checks. Use `:infinity` to disable periodic\n  checks after startup.\n  Default: `%Duration{hour: 6} |> to_timeout()`.\n\nPruning semantics:\n\n- one prune pass is always executed immediately on startup,\n- when `:prune_interval != :infinity`, additional periodic prune passes are scheduled,\n- when `:prune_interval == :infinity`, no periodic passes are scheduled after the initial startup\n  pass.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#module-configuration"},{"type":"module","title":"Option resolution order - Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager","doc":"For each server option, effective value is resolved in this order:\n\n1. option passed to `start_link/1` / supervisor child spec,\n2. application environment key under `:spex`,\n3. the default value.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#module-option-resolution-order"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.all_impl_models/0","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.all_impl_models/0`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#all_impl_models/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.all_instances/0","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.all_instances/0`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#all_instances/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.all_instances/1","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.all_instances/1`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#all_instances/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.child_spec/1","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.child_spec/1`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#child_spec/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.delete_instance/1","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.delete_instance/1`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#delete_instance/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.delete_instances/1","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.delete_instances/1`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#delete_instances/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.export_impl_models/0","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.export_impl_models/0`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#export_impl_models/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.get_instance/1","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.get_instance/1`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#get_instance/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.init_instance/4","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.init_instance/4`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#init_instance/4"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.init_instance!/4","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.init_instance!/4`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#init_instance!/4"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.init_instance_async/4","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.init_instance_async/4`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#init_instance_async/4"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.mock_instance!/4","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.mock_instance!/4`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#mock_instance!/4"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.start_link/1","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.start_link/1`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#start_link/1"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.transition/3","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.transition/3`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#transition/3"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.transition!/3","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.transition!/3`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#transition!/3"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.transition_async/3","doc":"Callback implementation for `c:Spex.InstanceManager.transition_async/3`.","ref":"Spex.InstanceManager.SimpleInstanceManager.html#transition_async/3"},{"type":"behaviour","title":"Spex.Specification","doc":"Behaviour and DSL for defining specifications through labelled transition systems (LTSs).","ref":"Spex.Specification.html"},{"type":"behaviour","title":"Configuration Options - Spex.Specification","doc":"Pass options to `use Spex.Specification, ...`.\n\n### `:transition_timeout`\n\nMaximum time between two observed transitions for an instance.\n\n- Default: `:infinity`\n- Accepted values: `:infinity`, integer milliseconds, or `%Duration{}` (anything accepted by\n  `Kernel.to_timeout/1`)\n- Used by instance manager timeout checks.\n\nIf an instance exceeds this timeout, Spex emits\n`%Spex.Errors.TransitionError{reason: :transition_timeout}` and routes it through the\nspecification `error_handler/2`.\n\n### `:prune_timeout`\n\nMinimum idle time before an instance can be considered for pruning.\n\n- Default: `:infinity`\n- Accepted values: `:infinity`, integer milliseconds, or `%Duration{}` (anything accepted by\n  `Kernel.to_timeout/1`)\n\nPruning eligibility also depends on `:prunable_states`.\n\n### `:prunable_states`\n\nControls which states are allowed to be pruned after `:prune_timeout`.\n\n- Default: `[]` (no states are prunable)\n- Accepted values:\n  - `:all`: any current state may be pruned\n  - `:terminal`: only terminal states (those without outgoing transitions) may be pruned\n  - explicit state list, e.g. `[:done, :failed]`; note that these are the states of your\n    implementation model, i.e. those used in `Spex.init_instance/4` and `Spex.transition/3`, which\n    may differ from the states of the specification","ref":"Spex.Specification.html#module-configuration-options"},{"type":"behaviour","title":"Transition DSL - Spex.Specification","doc":"Define transitions with `def_transition from_state, action, to_state`.\n\nEach call contributes to compile-time metadata used to generate:\n\n- `states/0`\n- `actions/0`\n- `transitions/0`\n- `initial_state/0`\n- `terminal_states/0`\n\nDuplicate states/actions/transitions are deduplicated.\n\nThe initial state is the source state of the first declared transition.","ref":"Spex.Specification.html#module-transition-dsl"},{"type":"behaviour","title":"Generated Callbacks - Spex.Specification","doc":"When you `use Spex.Specification`, the following callbacks are generated\nautomatically:\n\n- `transition_timeout/0`\n- `prune_timeout/0`\n- `prunable_states/0`\n- `states/0`\n- `actions/0`\n- `transitions/0`\n- `initial_state/0`\n- `terminal_states/0`\n- `error_handler/2` (delegates to `default_error_handler/2` by default)\n\n`error_handler/2` is overridable.","ref":"Spex.Specification.html#module-generated-callbacks"},{"type":"behaviour","title":"Error Handling Contract - Spex.Specification","doc":"`error_handler/2` receives `(error, caller_pid)` and must return:\n\n- `:ok` to swallow/accept the error condition, or\n- `{:error, reason}` to propagate failure.\n\nDefault behaviour in `default_error_handler/2`:\n\n- logs the error and caller stacktrace,\n- returns `:ok` for:\n  - `%Spex.Errors.TransitionError{reason: :deviation_still_equivalent}`\n  - `%Spex.Errors.ImplModelError{reason: :impl_model_not_found}`\n- returns `{:error, error}` for all other errors.","ref":"Spex.Specification.html#module-error-handling-contract"},{"type":"behaviour","title":"Full Example - Spex.Specification","doc":"defmodule MySpec do\n      use Spex.Specification,\n        transition_timeout: 30_000,\n        prune_timeout: %Duration{hour: 1},\n        prunable_states: :terminal\n\n      def_transition :idle, :start, :running\n      def_transition :running, :complete, :done\n      def_transition :running, :fail, :failed\n\n      @impl Spex.Specification\n      def error_handler(error, caller) do\n        super(error, caller)\n\n        # swallow all errors\n        :ok\n      end\n    end","ref":"Spex.Specification.html#module-full-example"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.Specification.error_handler_return/0","doc":"The return type for `error_handler/2` callbacks.","ref":"Spex.Specification.html#t:error_handler_return/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.Specification.t/0","doc":"A module implementing this behaviour","ref":"Spex.Specification.html#t:t/0"},{"type":"callback","title":"Spex.Specification.error_handler/2","doc":"Callback for handling errors emitted by Spex during instance management.","ref":"Spex.Specification.html#c:error_handler/2"},{"type":"macro","title":"Spex.Specification.def_transition/3","doc":"Defines a transition from one state to another via an action.\n\nThe first state of the first transition becomes the initial state.\nStates and actions are automatically collected and deduplicated.","ref":"Spex.Specification.html#def_transition/3"},{"type":"macro","title":"Example - Spex.Specification.def_transition/3","doc":"def_transition :idle, :start, :working\n    def_transition :working, :complete, :idle","ref":"Spex.Specification.html#def_transition/3-example"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.Specification.default_error_handler/2","doc":"Default error handling strategy used by specification modules.","ref":"Spex.Specification.html#default_error_handler/2"},{"type":"module","title":"Spex.Testing","doc":"Test helpers for preparing and manipulating Spex runtime state.","ref":"Spex.Testing.html"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.Testing.opt/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.Testing.html#t:opt/0"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.Testing.mock_instance!/4","doc":"Inserts or updates a mock instance at a specific state for test setup.\n\nUse this in unit tests to setup an instance without affecting the impl_model.","ref":"Spex.Testing.html#mock_instance!/4"},{"type":"function","title":"Spex.Testing.prepare_for_test_suite/1","doc":"Prepares after-suite hooks that export collected implementation models.\n\nCall this in your `test_helper.exs`.\n\nIt accepts the following opts:\n\n- `:instance_manager`: An instance manager module. By default, it uses the configured default\n  instance manager (see `m:Spex#module-using-other-instance-managers`). Specify this if you are\n  starting your instance manager in your supervision tree directly.\n- `:impl_models_dir`: Path to the directory where collected implementation models are exported\n  after tests. By default, this is the configured implementation models directory (see\n  `m:Spex#module-configuration`).","ref":"Spex.Testing.html#prepare_for_test_suite/1"},{"type":"exception","title":"Spex.Errors.DetsError","doc":"DETS backend operation errors.","ref":"Spex.Errors.DetsError.html"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.Errors.DetsError.reason/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.Errors.DetsError.html#t:reason/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.Errors.DetsError.t/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.Errors.DetsError.html#t:t/0"},{"type":"exception","title":"Spex.Errors.ImplModelError","doc":"ImplModel loading and lookup errors.","ref":"Spex.Errors.ImplModelError.html"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.Errors.ImplModelError.reason/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.Errors.ImplModelError.html#t:reason/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.Errors.ImplModelError.t/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.Errors.ImplModelError.html#t:t/0"},{"type":"exception","title":"Spex.Errors.InstanceError","doc":"Instance lifecycle errors such as duplicate or missing identifiers.","ref":"Spex.Errors.InstanceError.html"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.Errors.InstanceError.reason/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.Errors.InstanceError.html#t:reason/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.Errors.InstanceError.t/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.Errors.InstanceError.html#t:t/0"},{"type":"exception","title":"Spex.Errors.TransitionError","doc":"Transition-level error used for deviations and timeout conditions.","ref":"Spex.Errors.TransitionError.html"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.Errors.TransitionError.reason/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.Errors.TransitionError.html#t:reason/0"},{"type":"type","title":"Spex.Errors.TransitionError.t/0","doc":"","ref":"Spex.Errors.TransitionError.html#t:t/0"},{"type":"extras","title":"Spex","doc":"# Spex\n\n\\[This readme file has been written without the use of AI. The code and other documentation were written partially AI-assisted.\\]\n\nSpex is a tool to check the correctness of implementations against specifications. Concretely, it provides ways to (1) define specifications, (2) derive implementation models, and (3) check these against each other w.r.t. behavioural equivalence.\n\nIn this way, it is an attempt to bring a practical slice of formal verification theory into Elixir practice, allowing you to be more confident in the correctness of your implementations and helping you catch bugs and prevent unintended behaviours, especially in complex, multi-step workflows and protocols, possibly with asynchronous steps and concurrency. \nYou can think of it similar to a type system (or a layer above that), in that the annotations Spex requires you to provide can help you both to make your code more easily readable as well as to catch bugs early on; but instead of checking for type correctness, Spex checks for behavioural correctness.\n\nThe three primary concepts of Spex are specifications, instances, and implementation models: you define specifications, initialise instances of these specifications and record their state transitions, and from this the Spex engine derives an implementation model for the given specification.\n\nMore details on the formal concepts follow in the [Theoretical background](#theoretical-background) section below.","ref":"readme.html"},{"type":"extras","title":"How to use Spex (Quick start) - Spex","doc":"This section is a shortened version of the moduledoc of `Spex`. See there for details.","ref":"readme.html#how-to-use-spex-quick-start"},{"type":"extras","title":"Install, configure, and start Spex - Spex","doc":"Add Spex to your dependencies:\n\n```elixir\ndef deps do\n  [\n    {:spex, \"~> 0.1.1\", hex: :lts_spex}\n  ]\nend\n```\n\nPlease note the `hex: :lts_spex`.[^1] \n[^1]: The package name `:spex` itself was [already taken](https://hex.pm/packages/spex) (which I realised only after becoming attached to the name). However, since that package is unmaintained and not widely used, I decided to keep the namespace simply as `Spex`. The _lts_ prefix stands for _labelled transition system_ (see the [Theoretical background](#theoretical-background) section).\n\nOptionally, add `:spex` to your [`.formatter.exs` file under `:import_deps`](https://hexdocs.pm/mix/main/Mix.Tasks.Format.html#module-importing-dependencies-configuration).\n\n#### Configuration\n\nThe derived implementation models are stored in a custom format in a given folder. Ideally, this should be within the priv directory of your application (`:code.priv_dir(:your_app)`).\n\n```elixir\nconfig :spex, impl_models_dir: Path.join(:code.priv_dir(:your_app), \"spex_impl_models\")\n```","ref":"readme.html#install-configure-and-start-spex"},{"type":"extras","title":"Define specifications - Spex","doc":"Specifications represent protocols or workflows and are modelled as graphs / state machines. The focus lies on the transitions (edges) rather than the states (nodes): when we compare an implementation model against its specification, their states can be entirely distinct, since behavioural equivalence is judged entirely based on their transition behaviours (basically: action sequences).\n\nIn the simplest case, you can create a specification as follows:\n\n```elixir\ndefmodule YourApp.Specifications.Tree do\n  @moduledoc \"\"\"\n  A specification that forms a small, simple tree structure:\n\n               s0\n              /  |\n            a/    |a\n            /      |\n          s1       s2\n          / |\n        b/   |c\n        /     |\n      s3      s4\n\n  \"\"\"\n  use Spex.Specification\n\n  def_transition :s0, :a, :s1\n  def_transition :s0, :a, :s2\n\n  def_transition :s1, :b, :s3\n  def_transition :s1, :c, :s4\nend\n```\n\nEach _transition_ consists of a _from\\_state_, an _action_, and a _to\\_state_.\n\nSpecifications can have custom error handlers, to which any reported errors are passed for processing, e.g. logging and deciding which errors are okay.","ref":"readme.html#define-specifications"},{"type":"extras","title":"Observe transitions in your implementation - Spex","doc":"In your actual implementation code, you need to initialise instances of your specification and record transitions.\n\nAs a useless toy example, say we manage a pine forest where each pine has a number. We offer a function for planting a seedling:\n\n```elixir\nalias YourApp.Specifications.Tree\n\ndef plant_seedling(pine_id) do\n  specification = Tree\n  instance_identifier = {Tree, pine_id}\n  meta = %{planting_datetime: DateTime.utc_now()}\n  initial_state = :seedling\n\n  Spex.init_instance(specification, instance_identifier, meta, initial_state)\nend\n```\n\nNote that the instance identifier is an arbitrary term that uniquely identifies the instance across all specifications (hence it can make sense to include the specification module). The meta can optionally be added to make possible error reports regarding the instance more useful. The initial state is also optional and defaults to the specification's initial state.\n\nAfter an instance is initialised, we can record its transitions with `Spex.transition(instance_identifier, action, new_state)`:\n\n```elixir\ndef pour_onto(pine_id, :water), do: Spex.transition({Tree, pine_id}, :a, :sapling)\ndef pour_onto(pine_id, :oil), do: Spex.transition({Tree, pine_id}, :a, :withered)\ndef observe_growth(pine_id), do: Spex.transition({Tree, pine_id}, :__internal__, :mature_tree)\ndef cut_down(pine_id), do: Spex.transition({Tree, pine_id}, :b, :lumber)\ndef burn(pine_id), do: Spex.transition({Tree, pine_id}, :c, :ash)\n```\n\nAs mentioned above, the states do not have to match the specification states. The actions, however, do need to match, as these are what the behavioural equivalence is judged on. \n\nAn exception to this and a useful addition is the `__internal__` action, which can be used to record internal state transitions that are not part of the specification but that you still want to be recorded in the implementation model. These are ignored (or rather: treated specially) for the behavioural equivalence checks.","ref":"readme.html#observe-transitions-in-your-implementation"},{"type":"extras","title":"Derive implementation models: in tests - Spex","doc":"Your tests should cover all possible transitions of your implementation, so we can use them to derive an implementation model. To do this, add the following to your `test_helper.exs`:\n\n```elixir\nSpex.Testing.prepare_for_test_suite()\n```\n\nThis prepares the Spex engine to record all transitions from tests and write derived implementation models in the directory configured above.\n\nIn unit tests, we often construct our parameters to be in a certain state. When using `Spex.init_instance/4`, though, the given initial state is added as an initial state of the implementation model, which we don't want in these cases. To construct an instance in a certain state without affecting the implementation model, there is `Spex.Testing.mock_instance!/4`. In a test for our pine forest above, you might do something like this:\n\n```elixir\nalias YourApp.Specifications.Tree\n\nSpex.Testing.mock_instance!(Tree, {Tree, 1}, :mature_tree)\n\nassert YourApp.Pine.cut_down(1) == :ok\n```\n\nSince `cut_down/1` calls `Spex.transition({Tree, pine_id}, :b, :lumber)`, this test would add a transition from state `:mature_tree` with action `:b` to state `:lumber` to the implementation model.","ref":"readme.html#derive-implementation-models-in-tests"},{"type":"extras","title":"Check behavioural equivalence: offline - Spex","doc":"After implementation models have been derived and stored, you can run `mix spex` (see `Mix.Tasks.Spex`) to check whether they are behaviourally equivalent. Currently, the output only tells you _if_ an implementation model is not behaviourally equivalent to its specification and you are required to analyse the model to understand why.","ref":"readme.html#check-behavioural-equivalence-offline"},{"type":"extras","title":"Check behavioural equivalence: online - Spex","doc":"Once you have derived implementation models that were deemed behaviourally equivalent to their specification, you are ready to use Spex in production. Every time you initialise and instance or record a transition, it is checked whether the initialisation or transition is part of the implementation model. If it is, all is well. If it isn't, a behavioural equivalence check on the resultant model against the specification is run. In any case, an `%Spex.Errors.InstanceError{}` is reported, either with `:reason` being `:deviation_still_equivalent` or `:deviation_not_equivalent`. It is up to your specification's error handler to handle these cases accordingly (e.g. log the occurrence but still return `:ok` in the `:deviation_still_equivalent` case; this is what the default error handler does). The reason is that even deviations that don't break the equivalence hint at scenarios your tests don't cover. You can then fix these reports in the future by adding a test that covers the transition or by adding the transition manually to your implementation model.","ref":"readme.html#check-behavioural-equivalence-online"},{"type":"extras","title":"Theoretical background - Spex","doc":"Spex is motivated by ideas from concurrency theory and behavioural semantics. It is intended to be a light form of a refinement checker that does not require complex, static code analysis or manual proofs.\n\nThe primary theoretical model in Spex is that of _labelled transitions systems_ (LTSs): an LTS consists of a set of states and a set of transitions between those states, each transition being labelled by an action. The possible sequences of actions an LTS allows describe the behaviour of the system it models, roughly speaking. The idea behind Spex is that both specifications as well as implementation models can be described through LTSs. \n\n_Bisimilarity_ is a way to compare two LTSs and to deem them behaviourally equivalent based on these action sequences. The concrete definition of behavioural equivalence used by Spex is called _branching bisimilarity_. This is a relation between two LTSs that considers them equivalent if they can simulate each other's behaviour, while allowing for some flexibility in terms of internal transitions. The idea is that two systems are considered equivalent if they can perform the same sequences of observable (i.e. non-internal) actions, even if they may differ in their internal workings or states.\n\nTo learn more about the theory, you might start by going to the Wikipedia page for any of the terms above. You might also read the sections 2.1 and 2.2 of my [Bachelor's thesis](https://maxpohlmann.github.io/Reducing-Reactive-to-Strong-Bisimilarity/thesis.pdf) (skipping the _Isabelle_ sections, which formalise the notions in the Isabelle theorem prover). (The main part of the thesis is not related to Spex.)\n\nThe particular form of bisimilarity used by Spex is . To learn more about branching bisimilarity, you can read e.g. the following paper:\n\n> Van Glabbeek, R.J., Weijland, W.P.: Branching time and abstraction in bisimulation semantics. JACM 43(3), 555–600 (1996). https://doi.org/10.1145/233551.233556\n\nHere is the paper describing the algorithm Spex uses under the hood for determining branching bisimilarity:\n\n> Martens, J., Laveaux, M. (2026). Faster Signature Refinement for Branching Bisimilarity Minimization. In: Junges, S., Katz, G. (eds) Tools and Algorithms for the Construction and Analysis of Systems. TACAS 2026. Lecture Notes in Computer Science, vol 16505. Springer, Cham. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-032-22752-2_23\n\nThe algorithm was implemented in Rust in the crate [`merc_reduction`](https://docs.rs/merc_reduction/1.0.0/merc_reduction/) and used in Spex through a NIF. I want to thank [Maurice Laveaux](https://github.com/mlaveaux) for implementing this tool and making it available!","ref":"readme.html#theoretical-background"}],"proglang":"elixir","content_type":"text/markdown","producer":{"name":"ex_doc","version":"0.40.2"}}